Unpopular opinion here but I don't think this girl should be antagonised completely, I just think she was more practical and honest in terms of what her goals are for her when she is entering into this field of work. I think another important factor to also understand is the Chinese culture - usually it is common for men to show their affection by spending money on their partner. In fact, some guys would even see it as a rejection of their affection if a girl happens to reject their offer to pay for their things, etc. I think women from China are quite  'practical' in the sense that if they're being offered money, they will take it and men are therefore accustomed to winning affections like that. It's not as if they are forcing them to pay X amount. I don't think as well, the man will expect something from the women even after they offered their money. Although I don't agree with the idea that men should be expected to pay up to thousands of dollars for a partner, you also got to expect that your money WILL be taken if you offer it because some people are just like that. Simple. If the men wanted to offer the money (which is not required) and then expect the women to comply with how she behaves which will make him happy, then that's just narcissism. Also, I think a lot of people is expecting her to have some sort of passion or 'care' about this line of work. Some people do - and that's good for them! Unfortunately, she doesn't, and that's valid. If she really wanted to be a good person and nice, you don't have to do that for money. You can do it for free. You can simply be compassionate to anyone you see on the street. Obviously, this women isn't here to do that. She's here to receive money and that's her goal. You can't shame her for entering into this business and then trying to fake and sugar coat this service for the sake of the interviewer. If you wanted her to act and perform for this video, then you might as well write up a script for her to talk about! Again, I'm not trying to incite any sort of heated argument here, but this is just my opinion. I also don't personally like it when women are too materialistic - but hey, that's just how some people work and we got to respect that. Not everyone has to comply to our expectations of how they should or shouldn't behave. We can only just choose to stay in a relationship or walk away. In this case, if the guy that rented this girl didn't like her during the date, then why would they offer money at the end of it? They're to blame for their own actions too.

When I learned about this possibility of renting a GF or BF in Asia, I started to think how this renting is not in any way fulfilling the advertised promise, or the reason of this business.  I am not sure how those people, who rent these sorts of people, think. How they perceive it.  I see it as a pointless thing, especially for men, because what's the point here, to not feel lonely? It does the opposite, it shows you how desperate your are, how much you want to know how it is to have a GF/BF, but at the end you wont feel how it actually is, because it wasn't authentic, you will realize that this girl/guy has been with many random other people done the same thing. It's a stranger, a pretty stranger and that's it, they don't care about you, just the income, because it's business.  If they cared, they already would've had a legit boyfriend or just be alone unable to find a pair, but not to earn from pretending for a limited time to be a partner that you can't even kiss, only hand holding or...feeding each other, and one of them is just sucking money off of the other out.  Personally I can't comprehend how people using these services do not have the slightest idea of how this works, how fake it is, or maybe they do, but they hope to have something out of it, something they never will gain by using these services. Personally I would feel stupid if I rented a GF that will fake for me, and will allow only hand holding at best, or hand shaking at worst. Because kissing and romance in general is not possible in that sort of business, the whole deal wont feel satisfying at the end.  Paying to play board games or something feels weird too...don't they have some groups online through which they can interact and make meetups, and play with more people together in spare time without paying anything, or maybe some small fee? Maybe because they lack that sort of community groups that they have these sort of weird services that for some reason actually work there.

She seems like she has an incredibly screwed-up impression of relationships, love and affection...  I wonder if she even believes that those things exist?  I don't mean to sound Ethnocentric, but it seems like it's very common for people in China to have really messed-up misunderstandings about basic human sentiments, love and relationships.  I was there for several months and lived in several different cities in the mainland, and whenever conversations of this nature would come up, there seemed to either be a lot of immature naivety or rather cold/indifferent sentiment about these issues.  I encountered very few (younger) people who seemed to really have a somewhat healthy and conscious understanding of love/sex/relationships and so on... so many people just seemed so self-centered about it, which was strange because China is a VERY other-oriented, culture... I learned a lot from China about understanding the impact of doing what's best for the group and not just seeking your own self-interest.  As far as cultural-norms goes, I feel like Americans (we, who tend to be the more self-entitled and self-oriented types as a culture) could actually learn a lot from Chinese culture when it comes to being community minded.  I sometimes wonder if the impact of Western culture has lead to a lot of this newer, more self-entitled way of approaching relationships.       I get that the culture is different and all and I'm not intentionally judging an entire people group, but I feel like this is something that is finally starting to change or improve in Asia in general, China in particular.

Grease and flour 2 (8 1/2 by 4 1/4 by 2 1/2-inch) loaf pans. You may also line the bottom with parchment paper, if desired. Step 2: Cream the butter and 2 cups granulated sugar in the bowl of an electric mixer fitted with the paddle attachment, until light and fluffy, about 5 minutes. With the mixer on medium speed, add the eggs, 1 at a time, and the lemon zest. Step 3: Sift together the flour, baking powder, baking soda, and salt in a bowl. In another bowl, combine 1/4 cup lemon juice, the buttermilk, and vanilla. Add the flour and buttermilk mixtures alternately to the batter, beginning and ending with the flour. Divide the batter evenly between the pans, smooth the tops, and bake for 45 minutes to 1 hour, until a cake tester comes out clean. Step 4: Combine 1/2 cup granulated sugar with 1/2 cup lemon juice in a small saucepan and cook over low heat until the sugar dissolves. When the cakes are done, allow to cool for 10 minutes. Remove the cakes from the pans and set them on a rack set over a tray or sheet pan; spoon the lemon syrup over them. Allow the cakes to cool completely. Step 5:For the glaze, combine the confectioners' sugar and the lemon juice in a bowl, mixing with a wire whisk until smooth. Pour over the tops of the cakes and allow the glaze to drizzle down the sides.

@afro symphony This question actually got me thinking a little bit more , ty for that xD. As you implicitly state "acceptable" is actually a relative term. Sure, what may be acceptable to you may not be acceptable to me. This is totally legitimate and was one of the points I tried to get at: people choose what is "acceptable" to themselves whether they adopt the conventional standard or like many people seemingly are here, more liberal and think of and do things differently.  The issue arises where the girl sells '"moment's" to her clients on a strict basis. The implication with this however is that these "moment's" are generally found in courtships and monetizing them essentially devoids them of value within a relationship. Again the question is asked, how would you feel if your wife/gf offered this 'service' of whispering sweet nothings to a client during the day and coming home during the night and say the same to you? Would those words be as valuable or meaningful as they were if they were said exclusively to you?  The issue of moral/ethical degradation arises whereby, if you feel its inappropriate but she doesn't, shes causing you harm (emotionally at least) and if she feels its okay because her intentions are still pure then that would constitute an act of selfishness. If both parties find it acceptable then the requisites for relationship have just been lowered. And so, referring back to the above, people are choosing to lower passing criterias and may even find it acceptable to themselves if they are deluding others (the clients) and potentially inflicting emotional pain upon their partner and as a whole defacing the "sanctity/essence" of relationship.  There are core attributes to what defines a 'relationship' and no matter what age you are in it will persist, like it has throughout human history and in nature itself. This fractal of nature is intrinsic and can't be removed.

Whether you agree with her choice of profession or not, it's not illegal and there is a demand for her services in China.  Her approach to this work is very clinical, procedural and professional.  In a country of over a billion people, getting ahead (i.e., not working in a factory job) is not an easy task.  Clearly, there will be an inclination for good looking women to leverage their looks to gain an advantage, but that's true in many countries and societies where good career opportunities are limited.  It is interesting to see that she is doing this work long enough where she is completely devoid of romantic affection or even faking sincerity.  She's just very nonchalant or matter of fact about the whole encounter; even when being filmed.  If you are pretending to be someone's girlfriend, you got to at least pretend to be somewhat affectionate (i.e., flirting, superficial touching or caressing) with the client.  But I guess once you go down that road, the client has the wrong impression and then she gets put in a situation where money is offered in exchange for sexual acts.  Nonetheless, this is a very interesting video about modern Chinese life.

This young woman is a brilliant entrepreneur.  She's got a good head on her shoulders and is very smart in the exact details of how she runs her business.  As a woman, I don't think this is degrading at all, period.  As for Kei, I highly doubt he has trouble getting dates with those good looks, nice smile and most importantly, the respectful way he treats women. ;)  I did want to comment on one thing, where she replied that, "she doesn't care" about how the men feel after the date is over... say you were admitted to a hospital for a week or more after a bad accident. You get attached to the kind nurses whom attend to you during your care.  After you're discharged, you more than likely will not see those nurses again, probably for life.  Does that mean that those nurses wouldn't care to know that you are doing well for the "one-time" service they performed for you?  Back to this example, I'm sure it's not that Zhuang Zhou is "utterly inhuman and uncaring" as some people have indirectly implied in the other comments.  It's that she, like the nurses in my example, performed a one-time service.  Just because the service highly involves the human emotion of kindness, does not negate the fact that it is STILL a one-time service.  Not to mention in Zhuang Zhou's, that the men paying for her services were told IN ADVANCE to not expect "further feelings to develop" from her for said services.  Basically, when you RENT a girlfriend/boyfriend, don't ask for more services than what's in the Terms of Service. Â @skipperdon83Â  Racism is scarce. There is a difference between racism and discrimination. Propensities within a group of people to act   in particular ways that are noticeable train the mind to make correlations between appearance and actions/behaviors. This, coupled with the fact that people of external appearance and culture tend to associate and gather together also spreads and enforces the manifestation of particular behaviors and dispositions. Most people do not understand the definition and significance of racism, and instead, use it as a blanket term with loaded sentiments to invoke negative feelings towards someone who is speaking poorly of a group of people, especially of they are a minority. Racism is the belief in the inherent determinism of particular traits as to distinguish people as inferior or superior on a genetic basis. Do you really think every single person who speaks out against certain groups of people are racist? The principle is usually not any different than speaking out against Antifa, SJWs, Liberals, etc. The collective group is merely a population within a designated subset where certain qualities, ideas, or traits are being attributed to them as being greater in propensity, or characteristic of them. Similarly, when using a race as a group, it does not necessarily mean that every single member of the race is being attributed as being inherently disposed to certain stereotypes or beliefs, but rather, due to the aforementioned affects of culture amongst people of similar appearance and proximity, certain races tend to act in noticeably different ways in a generally different proportion compared to other groups, not on the basis of genetics, but other social elements. This means the basis is not "because" they are chinese, or black, but that they "happen" to be so. This is a serious distinction majority of people do not understand or realize. The dynamics of generalities actually extend much further, but ill leave the rest for you to contemplate. Here in the US, most cases of supposed racism are not only false, but cases of blacks being shot is usually due to three reasons. 1. Nearly all cases of blacks being shot by cops happens in areas where there is exponentially more crime caused by blacks, which also means cops subconsciously or consciously are much more cautious around blacks, as they have encountered plenty of cases in the past where they lie and use that to their advantage to attack cops or try to flee. 2. The ones being shot, nearly always were committing a crime right before being shot, and/or escalated the matter through aggressive language, body behavior, disobedience, and general lack of sense in rational conduct and manner. 3.Its part of human nature to be less disposed  to take risks, especially when the consequences can be deadly. Cops know about how often there is murder and hate against cops, so they are significantly more careful and even afraid of potential escalation into a dangerous situation. You cant operate on faith alone. Expectation of a possible negative circumstance, and subsequent cases where its come true is more than enough for them to be very wary afterwards. Or would you take your hot girlfriend down a dark alley in a gang infested corner of chicago because you trust that its not likely that they will do anything to you? In summary, its all about the intention and dynamics of consideration when using generalities. Discriminating against people on the basis of behavior,character, certain practices, etc is perfectly valid and sensible, even where some racial group is used as the population group, as it doesnt mean the attributed characteristics are limited to them, or that every single one of them do it, but that there is a significantly higher chance within the group to do so.
